### Explanate on how you approach this problem

I tried to solve problem #1 first using different strategies. However, each time I tried to use nested loops I would always get the output of 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0, -1, -2, etc... This confused me for a while.

In addition, I had to really work on the way I asked the questions. Sometimes I wasn't clear about the type of questions I was asking or if I was asking enough questions for all the data to work properly. For example, you couldn't just say I want the price for a kilogram of nuts for there were extra steps.


### Learn anything from this assignment

I think this is going to help a lot with my math skills and data analysis (at least, I hope so). I feel like that is the only way for me to really excel at anything is to practice and if I didn't struggle it would be the same as practice. So, when I struggle and eventually succeed because I tried different strategies I will know what the best strategy will be to use in the future and I will know why it's the best strategy to use.

### What challenges/roadblocks did you hit/run into?


For each problem I kept getting off track because I got caught guessing and having to redo things. This wasn't just an issue of being lazy but at least in one case one of the problems required using a nested for loop and I was just too frustrated to get started.

Input:"Never forget!" It’s a mantra of the world’s oldest veterans. Those who fought in World War I are dead. As for the World War II veterans, they’re getting old. Only 250,000 of them remain. They can’t fight anymore. They can’t even march. But many of them still remember with a chilling detail how they fought, and how they left behind one of history’s darkest chapters. 

Every Veteran’s Day, parades and ceremonies bring these proud men and women onto the streets. This year there were even more. More to march, more to honor, more to appreciate, and more to remember. This year there were two Veteran’s Days for the American veteran. One celebrated a day of victory in World War II. Veterans marched. Flags were waved. Families cried, and everyone cheered.   For most it was a day for joy and reflection, and for some, it was their final parade. The other Veteran’s day honored American women who served in the military in the years between World War I and World War II. Vital to combat and critical to victory, female veterans marched as well. Flags were woven into their hair and tears also flowed. It was a day of remembrance; not just of wartime battles, but of a difficult time when women were expected to simply accept whatever responsibilities they were given, on and off the battlefield. It would be years before any American woman would even be allowed to enlist in the military full-time--and, even then, it was more than 40 years ago. Today, women represent 16% of the men and women in uniform. The military has even officially recognized certain veterans of the Korean War. 

These are proud veterans. Proud of what they left behind. And no one should ever have to question where these men and women belong. Not in peace or in war, in parades or in memorials, proud or humble, or in a country where they are welcome.

### Explanation:

The solution assumes that if the value is negative the difference between the input and the negative number is positive. For example -55+5= -60+5=45. 

So for negative numbers you start with the negative number and then subtract the input.  However this solution will not work for all values since you can subtract 0 from any negative number, and that will not always yield positive numbers.

The solution assumes the input will be a floating point number.  For example, 0.1 will be rounded to 0. Because of this if you have two inputs that are decimal point numbers with different decimal places in them, it can lead to a difference between values if they have rounded differently. 

The solution looks for integers, so values such as 7.69 may result in values such as 7 or 8.  If values aren't integers, they may be rounded to the nearest integer. 

### Examples

For example, assume int A is equal to 4, and int B is equal to -8. Then, A-B is equal to 6.

### Solution:

If the value is negative, the negative number is subtracted from the input. 
In order to avoid getting incorrect results by rounding for example, if you subtract 0 from -4, both cases are treated the same. 
For example:
```
int A = 10;
int B = -9;
if ( A-B < 0 ){
    A-B;
}
else{
    B - A;
}
```

```julia
#!/usr/bin/env julia

using Dates
using Base.Iterators

function solve(s)
    r, b1 = re(s)
    d1 = isempty(b1)? true : false

    # read in next line
    r = parse(Int, re(s))
    s = drop(s, 1)

    if r == 0
        return true
    end

    if d1
        s = replace(s, r, "")
        e, b2 = re(s) # read second line and re-init r
        d1 = isempty (b2)? true : false 
    else
        e = parse(Int, replace(s, r.))
    end


    return d1 && e > 0
end

function solve(list)
    a = find(list) do l
        solve(l)
    end

end
